===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=蜫,䖵}}
; “elder brother”
: From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*(g/k)əw-n||elder brother; senior male relative}}; cognate with {{och-l|舅|maternal uncle}} ({{zh-ref|Benedict, 1972}}; STEDT).
: Alternatively, it may be related to {{cog|mkh-mmn|ကော|tr=kao|t=elder brother}}, with nominal suffix ''-n'' added ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).
; “descendants; later”
: Perhaps from {{der|zh|mkh-pro|*kuun||child}}; cognate with Min {{zh-l|*囝|son; child}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}) and with ancient Chu dialect {{och-l|觀|id=1|child; offspring}} ({{zh-ref|Ye, 2014}}); cf. also some rear meanings of the characters {{och-l|丱|young child}}, {{och-l|鯤|roe; fish egg}} and {{och-l|鰥|id=1|roe}} ([[ibid.]]). In modern Wu dialects the character {{och-l|官}} is used to mean "children" ([[ibid.]]).
; “many; numerous”
: From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*m-kul||twenty; all}}; cognate with {{och-l|群|herd; all}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; STEDT).
; “quetta-”
: {{psm|zh|en|quetta-}}. Coined by the [[w:zh:全国科学技术名词审定委员会|China National Committee for Terminology in Science and Technology]] and the [[w:State Administration for Market Regulation|State Administration for Market Regulation]] on [[w:World Metrology Day|World Metrology Day]] in 2023 (20 May 2023).

{{lang|zh|昆}} is pronounced with aspirated initial {{IPAchar|/kʰ/}} instead of the expected {{IPAchar|/k/}} in the majority of modern varieties of Chinese. The {{IPAchar|/k/}} sound in {{ltc-l|昆}} was changed to {{IPAchar|/kʰ/}} during its historical development to avoid homophony with {{ltc-l|褌|underclothing}}, a word that was historically in vernacular use ({{zh-ref|Hirayama, 2005}}).

